`crates/ctx-brief` is a standalone binary crate: it turns a STATUS.md backlog item or free-text ask into an executor brief by driving `claude` CLI in two stages (gather, then plan) and writing the result to a fixed report path. Depending on this crate means invoking the `ctx-brief` binary; there is no library API beyond what tests exercise directly.

The crate splits into `src/` (the binary and its orchestration logic) and `tests/` (integration coverage against fakes). `src/` owns the actual contract — argument parsing, path derivation, the `Fs`/`Claude` trait seams, and the `CONTRACT` string that must track CLI behavior. `tests/` pins that contract with executable examples but does not enforce it at compile time: `tests/brief.rs`'s call-count and output-path assumptions must be kept in sync by hand with any change to `runner.rs`'s flow or `cli.rs`'s path derivation.

The shared invariant spanning both: the literal output path convention (e.g. `.context/.reports/briefs/item.md`) and the two-stage gather/plan flow are asserted in three places independently — `contract.rs`'s `CONTRACT` string, `runner.rs`'s actual logic, and `tests/brief.rs`'s hardcoded expectations — and a change to any one without the other two will pass some checks and silently break others.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory, so no divergence can be assessed.